/*



https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-substring-with-at-most-k-distinct-characters/description/
https://leetcode.com/explore/interview/card/facebook/5/array-and-strings/3017/
Given a string s and an integer k, return the length of the longest substring of s that contains at most k distinct characters.

 

Example 1:

Input: s = "eceba", k = 2
Output: 3
Explanation: The substring is "ece" with length 3.
Example 2:

Input: s = "aa", k = 1
Output: 2
Explanation: The substring is "aa" with length 2.
 

Constraints:

1 <= s.length <= 5 * 104
0 <= k <= 50



Hint:
let’s say it were:
s = "aabac", k = 2
The real danger comes when a character repeats later and masks earlier occurrences.

✅ Correct Strategy:
Instead of assuming s.charAt(start) is the character to evict:

You search the map for the character with the minimum last-seen index.

That one is truly the leftmost.
int delIndex = Collections.min(map.values());
map.remove(s.charAt(delIndex));
start = delIndex + 1;
🔁 Summary:
✅ You're right that map.put(c, end) always updates to the latest index.

❌ This means map.get(s.charAt(start)) doesn't guarantee it's pointing to the leftmost character anymore.

✅ Hence, we must search the map for the actual leftmost index using Collections.min().

*/



class Solution {
 
    int start=0;
    int maxLen=0;
    Map<Character, Integer> map=new HashMap<>();

    public int lengthOfLongestSubstringKDistinct(String s, int k) {

        for(int end=0; end<s.length(); end++){
            char c=s.charAt(end);
            map.put(c,end); // each step updating character with current index

            if(map.size()<=k){
                maxLen=maxLen<=end-start+1?end-start+1:maxLen;
            }else{
                int idx=Collections.min(map.values()); //left most index to release
                map.remove(s.charAt(idx));
                start=idx+1;
                
            }

        }

        return maxLen;
        
    }
}
